            <ArticleTitle>Brain metabolic activity associated with long-term memory consolidation.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>351-4</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>The use of day-old chickens trained on a single-trial passive avoidance task provides a useful paradigm for investigations into cellular mechanisms underlying memory formation. Pharmacological intervention studies indicate that there are three temporally identifiable stages of memory processing leading to the consolidation of information for this task. These stages, designated as short-term (STM; up to 15 min), intermediate-term (ITM; 15-55 min), and long-term (LTM; more than 55 min) memory, have been found to be sequentially dependent (Ng and Gibbs, 1989). In addition, ITM appears to consist of two physiologically distinguishable phases, A and B. Evidence in this laboratory suggests that the crossover between these ITM phases (at 30 min after training) represents a critical time-point for the triggering of LTM.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
